t Status to Lead has restarted, and the QLHV group Telegram session has ended. The QLHV 5p monitor is still running, which is good. Now I need to check what child subagents are active.\\n\\nLooking at the cron:ed2d0b5d child sessions, all three are done or failed. The cron:e7885813 session appears to have ended and restarted as a new cycle. I should also note that the `subagent:8bffa95f` is marked as failed with repeated 500 errors, but those are historical from earlier today. So the state changes from the baseline are that DTLX 5p Monitor has restarted, and the Agent Status to Lead has also restarted.\\n\\nThe main change that matters for reporting is the DTLX 5p Monitor restarting since it was previously done at 21:37. Looking back at the earlier cycles, this is actually expected behavior—cron:6f3323ef runs on a 5-minute cycle and constantly restarts. The previous cycle ended at 21:37 and now the next one started at 22:05, which is about 28 minutes later. From a state-monitoring perspective, this is normal operation.\\n\\nThe telegram:group:-5163901258 ending is a clearer state change. Let me verify when it actually ended by converting the timestamp to UTC.\\n\\nLooking at the duration and start time, the session ran for about 8 seconds and ended around 21:49 UTC on April 14th. But I'm seeing conflicting timestamps in the data—the message at 21:47 says it's still running, while the end timestamp suggests it finished at 21:49. I need to reconcile these different timestamps to understand the actual session lifecycle.\\n\\nThe baseline at 21:37 showed it as running, so by 22:11 it's clearly ended, which is a change from the previous state. The cron:e7885813 session also appears to have restarted with a new cycle since the last check.\\n\\nLooking at the session details more carefully, the old session ended around 20:45 UTC and a new one started at 21:34 UTC. By the 22:11 baseline, it had been running for about 37 minutes, and now at 22:11 it's still running after 22 